<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-755-332  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 755 332.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer-Aided Engineering  July 1990 v9 n7 p104(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Choosing an operating system. (includes related articles onmicrocomputer software developers and on Unix)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Potter, Caren D.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Deciding which operating system (OS) is best is not easy.andP;  DOS, acharacter-based OS, handles one application and one user at a timeand has a 640 kilobyte memory limit, a significant drawback.andP;  Buta new class of software, called DOS Extenders, removes this 640kilobyte limit and provides developers access to megabytes of RAM.andO;DOS Extenders are completely invisible to the user.andP;  One of DOS'smajor advantages is the large amount of mature software availablefor it.andP;  OS/2, developed jointly by Microsoft Corp and IBM, allowsmultitasking, access to up to 16 megabytes of memory, and iconsand windows.andP;  But OS/2 is still a single-user OS and does not havemuch application software, especially CAD software.andP;  Unix, amultiuser OS, supports multitasking, is fast, and has considerableapplications software.andP;  Its disadvantages are the many variationsthat exist and a relative shortage of applications software formicrocomputers running Unix.andP;  Unix may be the best choice forengineering organizations, especially since it is easy to networkwith Unix.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Operating SystemsUNIXMS-DOSOS-2EngineeringSoftware Selection.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Glossary. (table)Who's using extenders? (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>